record_data.record_plain_text: RATE SCHEDULE WHOLESALE FOR RESALE POWER SERVICE AVAILABILITY Available for each single point of service to wholesale Customers for loads of not less than 400 kilowatts at each point of delivery except as may otherwise be agreed between the Company and the Customer. For connections after December 1, 1994, the minimum capacity will be 200 KW for the first year, 250 KW for the second, and 300 KW for the third year and thereafter. MONTHLY RATE FOR EACH POINT OF SERVICE Customer Charge $158.00 Net Kilowatt Demand Charge $9.993 Net per kilowatt Reactive Kilovolt-Ampere Charge All Kilovars in Excess of 35% of the current Kilowatt Billing Demands $0.40 Net per Kilovar Energy Charge All kWh $0.02475 Net per kWh Kilowatthour Only Charge All kWh $0.04844 Net per kWh Billing for miscellaneous customers with kilowatthour only metering is based on the above kWh rate. No Customer Charge, Kilowatt Demand Charge, or Reactive Kilovolt-Ampere Charge shall apply. Automatic Tax Adjustment An adjustment for tax changes shall apply, as appropriate, to the kilowatt-hours or kilowatts billed under this rate schedule. Rates to be adjusted, as required, by including an automatic pass-through of changes in federal, state, or local taxes or tax rates by providing an automatic adjustment of all taxes, upward or downward, based on actual tax expense incurred by Monongahela Power Company. For changes in tax expense related to the Federal Corporate Income Tax rate, the appropriate dollar amount shall be applied on an apportioned demand basis. For all other taxes or tax rate changes, unless otherwise agreed to by the Parties, the appropriate dollar amount shall be applied on an apportioned kilowatt-hour basis. Fuel Adjustment A fuel cost adjustment shall apply to all kilowatthours billed under this rate schedule. The adjustment shall be determined by the following formula to the nearest 0.001 cent per kilowatthour: A={ Fm Fb} x L x 1 Sm Sb 1-T A = Fuel Cost Adjustment in cents per Kilowatthour Fm = Fuel Cost in the current period relating to: (a) Fossil and nuclear fuel consumed in generation in wholly-owned and jointly-owned stations and identifiable fossil and nuclear fuel costs in energy purchased plus the net energy cost of energy purchased on an economic dispatch basis less; (b) Fossil and nuclear fuel costs recovered through intersystem sales. All fuel costs will be those charged to Account 501, cleared through Account 151, and Account 518 in the month preceding the billing Month. Sm = All kilowatthour sales to regular Customers in the current period. Fb and Sb = Fuel and kilowatthour sales in the base period as defined above. The factor Fb = 1.70 cent per kilowatt-hour Sb L = Adjustment factor to recognize losses to service voltage where different than average losses in the delivery system. This factor is 0.97. T = The gross receipts tax rate in effect during the billing Month, expressed as a decimal. The amount of fuel adjustment shall not be subject to any discounts. LOCAL TAX ADJUSTMENT Within municipalities or political subdivisions which impose taxes based upon the amount of Electric Service supplied or revenues received by the Company, there shall be added to the total monthly bill a surcharge equal to the total bill multiplied by the surcharge rate. The surcharge rate shall be computed as follows: Surcharge Rate = Local Tax Rate 1-(Local Tax Rate + West Virginia State Tax Rate) MINIMUM CHARGE The monthly bill shall not be less than the billing demand charge. LATE PAYMENT CHARGE A late payment charge of 2% of the bill on the above net rates, including the fuel cost adjustment, will be made for failure to make payment in full within 20 days of the mailing date of the bill. DETERMINATION OF BILLING DEMAND The billing demand for any one-month period shall be the highest of the following: (a)The maximum Kw integrated over any fifteen-minute interval, or (b)400 Kw, or (c)50% of the Kw capacity specified in the Service Agreement, or (d)50% of the maximum billing demand previously established during the term of the Agreement, or (e)60% of the maximum billing demand in any of the twelve months prior to the billing Month. If there is a permanent transfer of load from one delivery point to another of the Customer, then the minimum demand calculation resulting from (c), (d) or (e) above for the delivery point losing the load will be based upon a new lesser value of capacity and demand as established by Company for future calculations of (c), (d) and (e). GENERAL Service supplied under this schedule is subject to power service voltage regulations. TERM As provided in the Electric Service Agreement, but not less than one year.

DESCRIPTION OF COMPANY SERVICE Monongahela Power Company, an Ohio corporation, does business as an electric utility in the states of Ohio and West Virginia and has interconnections with other electric utilities in neighboring states. It supplies electric service to retail customers in Ohio and West Virginia and to three wholesale for resale customers in West Virginia and two affiliated companies at state lines. The Company is subject to regulation by the Public Service Commission of West Virginia and the Public Utilities Commission of Ohio under the laws of those states.

RULES AND REGULATIONS The following Rules and Regulations govern the supply of wholesale Electric Service by Monongahela Power Company to wholesale Customers. 1.Definitions 1.1Certain words, when used in the Rules and Regulations, Rate Schedules and Agreements of Monongahela Power Company, shall have the following meanings: 1.1.1 Customer : Any wholesale Customer operating a distribution system and selling Electric Service to its customers 1.1.2 Company : Monongahela Power Company. 1.1.3 Service : Any electricity which the Company may supply or make provision to supply, or any work or material furnished, or any obligation performed by the Company under its Rules and Regulations or Rate Schedules. 1.1.4 Month : Approximately one-twelfth of a year, and may be any period of 25 to 35 consecutive days. 1.1.5 Service Connection : Each connection through which the Company furnishes Electric Service to the Customer. 2.Service Availability 2.1Character of Electric Service 2.1.1Unless otherwise specially agreed upon, the Company will furnish to a Customer three phase, sixty cycle alternating current at voltages between 10,000 and 100,000 from its overhead system. 2.1.2 Inasmuch as some of the above voltages are available only in certain sections of the territory served by the Company, it is necessary that the Customer consult the Company about the type of Service that will be supplied before proceeding with the installation of wiring or the purchase of equipment. 2.2Capacity 2.2.1The Company agrees to supply the capacity and energy requirements of the Customer specified in the Service Agreement. As the Customer s requirements change from time to time, the Customer agrees to notify the Company of such change, and the Company agrees to amend the Service Agreement to reflect such change and to supply the Customer s additional requirements to the extent that the Company has or can obtain the capacity to do so. The Company s existing facilities have a limited capacity; therefore, to assure satisfactory operation of the Customer s facilities and to protect both the Customer s and the Company s facilities against damage, the Company must be advised of any substantial change in the amount or use of the Customer s load from that specified in the current Service Agreement so that facilities of the proper capacity may be installed, provided, however, that such change shall be subject to availability of power on the Company s system and to agreement between the parties on such facilities or arrangements as may be required to ensure the reliability of both systems. The Customer shall pay for any damage or loss caused to the Company which results from a violation of this provision. 2.3Liability 2.3.1The Customer, by accepting Service from the Company, assumes full responsibility for the safety and adequacy of the Customer s wiring and equipment installed on the Customer s system. The Customer agrees to indemnify and save the Company harmless from any liability which may arise as the result of the use of or transmission of Service supplied to the Customer by the Company 2.4Use of Equipment 2.4.1The Customer shall not operate nor permit the operation of any equipment creating a condition which prevents the Company from supplying the satisfactory Service to others. 3.Agreement for Service 3.1The form of agreement for Service under this electric tariff shall be substantially as set out herein. 4.Right of Way 4.1The facilities of the Company, by which service is furnished, shall be located on or over easements which will provide a route deemed by the Company to be the most suitable for the furnishing of such Service. In consideration of the furnishing of Service by the Company, the Customer shall cause such rights and easements to be provided to the Company on or within the property to be served as the Company shall deem necessary and convenient to permit the construction, operation and maintenance of the Company s facilities required to serve the Customer; costs, if any, to be borne by the Customer. It shall not be the obligation of the Company to acquire any right or easement on or over property of another necessary for the furnishing of Service to the Customer for which acquisition the Company does not have the right of eminent domain. 5.Maintenance and Removal 5.1Facilities provided by the Company are the property of the Company and shall remain its property. The Customer shall permit the Company to inspect, maintain, and remove the Company s facilities at all reasonable hours. 6.Customer s Facilities 6.1The Customer shall pay the cost of relocating its facilities if such relocation is made necessary by a moving of the Company s facilities as required by law or public improvements. 7.Company s Facilities 7.1The Customer shall pay the cost of moving the Company s facilities if they are moved at the Customer s Request. 8.Continuity of Service 8.1The Company will use reasonable diligence in attempting to provide continuous Service. The Company shall not be liable for any loss, cost, damage or expense caused by any failure to supply electricity according to the terms of a contract, or by any interruption of the supply of electricity, reversal of the Service, variation in voltage or by any other failure, when such failures are due to acts of God, public enemies, accidents, strikes, riots, wars, extraordinary repairs and operating necessities, orders of Court or other Governmental authority, or to any other acts or conditions reasonably beyond the control of the Company. 8.2In the event of an emergency threatening the integrity of its system, the Company may, without liability, interrupt, curtail, or suspend Service. 8.3The Company agrees to give Customer a minimum of 7 days prior notice of planned maintenance which will result in interruption, voltage reduction, transfer of load or other curtailment or alteration of Service to Customer. If 7 days prior notice is not feasible for reasons of Service reliability, Company agrees to inform Customer as far in advance of planned maintenance as is possible. Company agrees to cooperate with Customer to minimize any interruption, voltage reduction or other impairment or curtailment of Service to Customer s consumers caused by Company s maintenance work. 9.Emergency Load Control 9.1Whenever the demands for power on all or part of the Company s system exceed or threaten to exceed the capacity then actually and lawfully available to supply such demands, or whenever system instability or cascading outages could result from actual or expected transmission overloads or other contingencies, or whenever such conditions exist in the system of another public utility or power pool with which the Company s system is interconnected and cause a reduction in the capacity available to the Company from that source or threaten the integrity of the Company s system, a load emergency situation exists. In such case, the Company shall take such reasonable steps as the time available permits to bring the demands within the then available capacity or otherwise control load. Such steps shall include, but shall not be limited to, reduction or interruption of Service to one or more Customers in accordance with the Company s procedures for controlling load. The Company and the Customer agree to coordinate their load control programs to minimize the possibility of having to interrupt Service to residential consumers or consumers supplying essential public services on the systems of either Company or Customer. Company agrees that to the extent possible it will promptly notify Customer when it begins or expects to begin implementation of its load control program if such implementation could reasonably be expected to affect the Customer and Customer agrees to cooperate with Company, by implementing Customer s load control program as needed to avoid an emergency which could threaten the integrity of Company s system. Company agrees that it will not interrupt Service to Customer without prior notice except under the conditions described in Sections 8.1 and 8.2 of these Rules and Regulations. 10.Metering 10.1For the purpose of measuring or obtaining such information as it may require for billing purposes, the Company may select and use any type of metering equipment, provided it meets the accuracy requirements of the West Virginia Public Service Commission. The accuracy of the metering equipment shall be verified by proper test at any time upon reasonable notice given by either of the parties to the other, and each party shall be entitled to have a representative present at such verification. The work of testing and adjusting any meter for accuracy shall be performed by and at the expense of the Company, provided that such test is not called for by the other party more often than once in twelve months. If either party shall require more than one verification of any meter in any twelve-month period, and the meter proves to be accurate within two (2) percent up or down, the additional verification shall be at the expense of the party requesting it. If such equipment is found to be inaccurate by more than two (2) percent up or down, the equipment shall be made accurate and the meter readings for the period of inaccuracy shall be adjusted to correct such inaccuracies as far as the same can be reasonably ascertained, but no adjustment prior to the beginning of the second preceding month shall be made except by agreement of the parties. In the event that the Company s meters fail to register properly during any billing period, the demand and energy quantities will be estimated by the Company and the Customer from the best available data. 11.Connections with Other Power Sources 11.1In order to insure safe operating practices in the event the Customer shall receive electric energy from a source of power supply other than the Company, adequate provision shall be made to insure that under no circumstances can the other power supply source be interconnected so as to operate in parallel with that of the Company, except by written consent of the Company. This tariff is applicable to firm partial requirements Service; but in the event Service supplied by the Company is desired to be used as an emergency or reserve Service to another source of supply, the Customer shall enter into negotiations for a separate agreement with the Company covering the rates, terms and conditions to apply to such Service. 12.Billing and Payment 12.1Bills for service will be rendered at regular monthly intervals in accordance with the then effective applicable rate schedule set out herein and shall be due upon presentation. 12.2Late payment charges will be applied to all undisputed bills as provided in the Rate Schedule set out herein if all previous undisputed bills have not been paid in full. If bills are paid by mail, the date of the postmark will be considered the date of payment. 13.Excess Facilities 13.1The rates in this tariff are based on the Customer connecting to existing facilities of the Company. If the Company is required to extend its lines or build any additional facilities to enable it to render Service as requested to the Customer, the Customer shall pay for the cost of such extensions or facilities in addition to its monthly bill for Electric Service. 14.Transfer of Agreement 14.1The Agreement between Customer and the Company is transferable only with the Company s written consent. 15.Cancellation of Contract 15.1The contract shall, at the option of the Company, cease and terminate, and all claims for Service previously delivered shall become forthwith due and payable in case of any act of receivership or bankruptcy by or against the Customer. 16.Notice Requirements 16.1Where notice to the Company is required under this tariff, such notice shall be directed to the Division Manager of the Division in which the Customer is located.

THIS FACILITIES LEASE AND ASSIGNMENT AGREEMENT (this “Lease”) is made and entered into as of one minute after 11:59 p.m. EPT on December 31, 2006 (the “Lease Date”), by and between Monongahela Power Company, an Ohio corporation, as lessor (“Mon Power”), and The Potomac Edison Company, dba Allegheny Power, a Maryland corporation, as lessee (“PE”). Each of Mon Power and PE shall be referred to herein individually as a “Party” and, collectively, as the “Parties.” WITNESSETH: WHEREAS, Mon Power, PE and Allegheny Energy Supply Company, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“AE Supply”) are subsidiaries of Allegheny Energy, Inc., a public utility holding company under the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005 (“PUHCA”); and WHEREAS, PE maintains a bundled retail service obligation in West Virginia; and WHEREAS, PE and AE Supply, entered into (a) that certain Facilities Lease Agreement (the “Original FLA”), dated as August 1, 2000, pursuant to which PE leased certain generating facilities from AE Supply, and (b) that certain Service Agreement (the “Original Service Agreement”), dated as of August 1, 2000, pursuant to which AE Supply supplied electric power to PE to meet its West Virginia Service Obligations; and WHEREAS, Allegheny Energy, Inc. desires to cause a realignment of the generating assets under its control and the contractual arrangements associated therewith to permit construction and finance, through state-authorized securitization, of flue gas desulfurization units at the Fort Martin Generating Station and to resolve certain state regulatory issues resulting from West Virginia’s decision to cease implementation of retail competition; and WHEREAS, in connection with such realignment, AE Supply desires to transfer to Mon Power interests in certain of AE Supply’s generating facilities, including certain facilities located in West Virginia, and assign to Mon Power certain contractual rights to a portion of the output of the Bath County Generating Station, and, in exchange, Mon Power wishes to transfer to AE Supply interests in certain of Mon Power’s generating facilities (such transactions, collectively, the “Transfer”); and WHEREAS, to reflect the occurrence of the Transfer and the realignment of generating assets and contractual arrangements (a) AE Supply wishes to assign its rights and obligations under the Original Service Agreement to Mon Power and Mon Power wishes to assume such rights and obligations, and (b) Mon Power and PE wish to amend and restate the Original Service Agreement in its entirety, and to this end, Mon Power and PE are entering into that certain Amended and Restated Full Requirements Service Agreement (the “Service Agreement”) on even date herewith, pursuant to which Mon Power will supply electric power to PE to meet its West Virginia Service Obligations; and WHEREAS, Mon Power has contractual rights to a portion of the output of the Bath County Generating Station, both through its Affiliate, Allegheny Generating Company, and pursuant to the Transfer; and WHEREAS, in addition to the Transfer and as part of the realignment of generating assets and contractual arrangements, AE Supply and PE are entering into that certain Termination Agreement (the “Termination Agreement”) on even date herewith, pursuant to which AE Supply and PE will terminate the Original FLA; and WHEREAS, to replace the generating facilities previously leased to PE pursuant to the Original FLA and to assign to PE a portion of Mon Power’s contractual rights to a portion of the output of the Bath County Generating Station, Mon Power and PE now wish to enter into this Lease on the terms and conditions set forth herein; and NOW, THEREFORE, and in consideration of the foregoing, and of the mutual promises, covenants and conditions set forth herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the Parties hereto, intending to be legally bound by the terms and conditions set forth in this Lease, hereby agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS 1.1 Definitions. As used m this Lease, the following terms shall have the following meanings: “Affiliate” means, with respect to any entity, any other entity that, directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, or is controlled by, or is under common control with, such entity. For this purpose, “control” means the direct or indirect ownership of fifty percent (50%) or more of the outstanding capital stock or other equity interests having ordinary voting power. “AE Supply” shall have the meaning set forth in the recitals hereto. “Ancillary Services” shall have the meaning set forth in the PJM Agreements. “B&O Tax” shall have the meaning set forth in Article 7 (Taxes) hereof. “Bankrupt” means, with respect to any entity, such entity: (i) voluntarily files a petition or otherwise commences, authorizes or acquiesces in the commencement of a proceeding or cause of action under any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization or similar law, or has any such petition filed or commenced against it by its creditors and such petition is not dismissed within sixty (60) calendar days of the filing or commencement; (ii) makes an assignment or any general arrangement for the benefit of creditors; (iii) otherwise becomes insolvent, however evidenced; (iv) has a liquidator, administrator, receiver, trustee, conservator or similar official appointed with respect to it or any substantial portion of its property or assets; or (v) is generally unable to pay its debts as they fall due. “Business Day” means any day except a Saturday, Sunday or a day that PJM declares to be a holiday, as posted on the PJM website. A Business Day shall open at 8:00 a.m. and close at 5:00 p.m. Eastern Prevailing Time. “Capacity” means, with respect to any Generating Facility(ies), the net normal maximum available capacity from such Generating Facility(ies) that can be used to satisfy any “Unforced Capacity” obligation as set forth in the PJM Agreements, or any successor capacity obligation of a Load Serving Entity as may be employed in PJM as set forth in the PJM Agreements. “Capital Addition” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 4.4 (Capital Additions). “Damage Event” means an Event of Loss or any event in which a Generating Facility shall suffer damage, loss, condemnation, confiscation, theft or seizure that does not constitute an Event of Loss. “Defaulting Party” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 12.1 (Events of Default) hereof. “Early Termination Date” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 12.2 (Remedies) hereof. “Eastern Prevailing Time” or “EPT” means Eastern Standard Time or Eastern Daylight Savings Time, whichever is in effect on any particular date. “ECAR” means the East Central Area Reliability Coordination Agreement or any successor agreement thereto. “Effective Date” means the date by which all the Effective Date Conditions are satisfied or waived by the applicable Party. “Effective Date Conditions” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 2.1 (Effective Date) hereof. “Energy” means three-phase, 60-cycle alternating current electric energy, expressed in units of kilowatt-hours or megawatt-hours. “Emergency Services” means emergency operation and maintenance services, including those services performed in case of explosion, fire, storm, sudden emergencies, sabotage or any unscheduled major interruption of the operation of the Leased Facilities. “Environmental Control Act” shall mean W. Va. Code § 24-2-4e (2005). “Environmental Control Activity” shall have the meaning ascribed to the term “Environmental control activity” set forth in the Environmental Control Act. “Environmental Control Bonds” shall have the meaning ascribed to the term “Environmental control bonds” set forth in the Environmental Control Act. “Environmental Control Cost” shall have the meaning ascribed to the term “Environmental control cost” set forth in the Environmental Control Act. “Environmental Control Cost Prepayment” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 6.2 (Environmental Control Cost Prepayment) hereof. “Environmental Control Equipment” shall have the meaning ascribed to the term “Environmental control equipment” set forth in the Environmental Control Act. “Equitable Defenses” means any bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization and other laws affecting creditors’ rights generally, and with regard to equitable remedies, the discretion of the court before which proceedings to obtain same may be pending. “Event of Loss” shall mean any of the following events: (i) the loss of a Generating Facility or use thereof due to destruction or damage to such Generating Facility that renders repair uneconomic or that renders such Generation Facility permanently unfit for normal use; (ii) any damage to a Generation Facility that results in an insurance settlement with respect to such Generation Facility on the basis of a total loss or an agreed constructive or a compromised total loss of such Generation Facility; or (iii) a requisition, condemnation, confiscation or taking of, or requisition of title to or ownership of, a Generation Facility by any Governmental Authority that shall have resulted in loss by Mon Power of title to or ownership of such Generation Facility. “Event of Default” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 12.1 (Events of Default) hereof. “FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor. “FERC Approval” shall mean all final and binding authorizations, acceptances or approvals by the FERC that may be required under Sections 203 and/or 205 of the Federal Power Act, as applicable, in order to make this Lease and the Service Agreement effective. “Force Majeure” means an event or circumstance that prevents one Party from performing its obligations hereunder, which event or circumstance was not foreseen as of the date this Lease is entered into, which is not within the reasonable control of, or the result of the negligence of the affected Party and which, by the exercise of due diligence, the Party is unable to mitigate or avoid or cause to be avoided. Notwithstanding the foregoing, under no circumstance shall an event of Force Majeure be based on: (i) changes in market conditions that affect the cost or availability of energy, capacity or ancillary services to either Party; or (ii) curtailment by a Transmitting Utility due to transmission congestion. “Full Requirements Service” shall have the meaning set forth in the Service Agreement. “Generating Facilities” shall have the meaning set forth in Section 3.1 (Leased Facilities) hereof. “Good Utility Operating Practice” means any of the practices, methods, standards, guides or acts: (a) required by any Governmental Authority, PJM (or other regional transmission organization or independent system operator that PE or Mon Power may become a member of), any regional or national reliability council, including NERC, ECAR, or the successor of any of them, or other applicable regional reliability council in which the Generating Facilities are located whether or not the Party whose conduct is at issue is a member thereof; (b) otherwise engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry within the region served by PJM (or other regional transmission organization or independent system operator that PE or Mon Power may become a member of), during the relevant time period which in the exercise of reasonable judgment, in light of the facts known, or that should have been known at the time a decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result in a manner consistent with applicable laws and regulations, good business practices, reliability (for generation, transmission and distribution), safety, environmental protection, economy, and expediency; ARTICLE 3 LEASE OF GENERATING FACILITIES AND ASSIGNMENT OF OUTPUT 3.1 Leased Facilities. Upon the terms and conditions set forth herein: (a) Mon Power hereby leases to PE, and PE hereby leases from Mon Power, a portion of its generating facilities equal to a fixed amount of 360 MW of the Generating Facilities (excluding the Bath County Generating Station) and in the specific MW amounts from each as listed on Exhibit A hereto; and (b) Mon Power hereby assigns to PE, and PE hereby assumes, a fixed portion of Mon Power’s contractual right (whether such rights have been transferred to Mon Power in accordance with the Transfer or acquired directly from its Affiliate, Allegheny Generating Company) to the output of the Bath County Generating Station in the amount of 65 MW (collectively, the leased and assigned MW, the “Lease MW Allotment”). The portion of Generating Facilities leased by Mon Power to PE and the MW output assigned by Mon Power to PE from the Bath County Generating Station, in each case, pursuant to this Lease, are for convenience referred to herein as the “Leased Facilities.” The description of facilities being leased contained on Exhibit A is intended to and shall exclude facilities booked to transmission and distribution under FERC’s Uniform System of Accounts or interpreted by FERC to be booked to transmission and distribution; provided, however, that the Leased Facilities (excluding the MW output assigned from the Bath County Generating Station) shall include a pro-rated portion of the generation step-up transformers associated with the Generating Facilities. With respect to any of the generating facilities listed in Exhibit A (the “Generating Facilities”), PE shall be entitled to the MWs specified in Exhibit A on a first priority basis. In the event that (i) the Capacity of any of the Generating Facilities is reduced, as a result of a planned or unplanned outage or derate or any other any reason, below the MWs specified in Exhibit A or (ii) any Capacity associated with the Leased Facilities is retired, mothballed or placed in cold storage, in either case (i) or (ii), in order to maintain the Lease MW Allotment at the specified level, the Operating Committee shall increase the MW levels to be leased or assigned from the remaining Generating Facilities on a pro rata basis to make up for any shortfall in the Lease MW Allotment. The Leased Facilities may be modified from time to time by decision of the Operating Committee, provided that the Lease MW Allotment remains constant. 3.2 Use and Enjoyment. Mon Power hereby grants unto PE, as lessee and assignee of the Leased Facilities, as applicable, the right to use and enjoy the Leased Facilities and all other rights in respect of the Leased Facilities set forth in this Lease for the exclusive benefit of its West Virginia customers. So long as no Event of Default has occurred and is continuing and subject to the terms and conditions of this Lease, PE’s quiet enjoyment of the use and operation of the Leased Facilities will not be disturbed by Mon Power or any of its Affiliates (other than PE) or any other person or entity having a rightful, valid and legal claim by, through or under Mon Power or any of its Affiliates (other than PE). 3.3 Title. This Lease shall constitute an agreement of lease and assignment and nothing herein shall be construed as conveying to PE any right, title or interest in or to the Leased Facilities except as lessee or assignee, as applicable, only. It is the intent of the parties that this Lease will be a true lease for all federal, state, city and local income or franchise tax purposes, and that Mon Power shall at all times be considered to be the lessor of the leased Generating Facilities for all federal, state, city and local income or franchise tax purposes. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Lease, ownership and title to the Leased Facilities, except with respect to the Bath County Generating Station, shall at all times remain with Mon Power. 3.4 Termination of Lease. Upon termination of this Lease, all interests in the Leased Facilities, including any Capital Additions made during the Term, subject to the terms of this Lease, shall revert to Mon Power. 3.5 Service Obligations. This Lease, in conjunction with the Full Requirements Service provided under the Service Agreement, is intended to provide PE with sufficient Capacity, associated Energy and Ancillary Services to meet its Service Obligations. Subject to the provisions of this Lease (including Section 3.3 (Title) and this Section 3.5), PE shall have an exclusive leasehold interest in or assignment of, as applicable, an undivided interest in the Capacity, associated Energy and Ancillary Services associated with the Leased Facilities. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in no event shall PE’s portion of Capacity, associated Energy and Ancillary Services in a given calendar month exceed PE’s Service Obligations for such calendar month. Mon Power shall remain entitled on an exclusive basis to any Capacity, associated Energy and Ancillary Services available from the Leased Facilities in excess of the amounts needed by PE to meet its Service Obligations and to all economic benefits derived therefrom (such as those benefits available through the Capacity, Energy and Ancillary Services markets administered by PJM) and shall remain responsible for any economic costs applicable thereto (such as those costs associated with future changes to PJM market rules applicable to the Leased Facilities). 3.6 Operating Lease. It is the understanding and intention of the Parties that this Lease is to be classified as an operating lease with respect to the leased Generating Facilities. To the extent that, by law or regulation, this Lease cannot be classified as an operating lease, the Parties agree to negotiate and implement in good faith amendments or other changes necessary to classify (or continue to classify) this Lease as an operating lease. 3.7 No Right to Sublease. PE shall have no right to sublease or assign the Leased Facilities without the consent of Mon Power, which consent may be withheld at Mon Power’s sole and absolute discretion. ARTICLE 4 OPERATION OF LEASED FACILITIES 4.1 Joint Operation. The Parties understand and agree that while, subject to the terms and conditions of this Lease, PE shall have an exclusive leasehold interest in or assignment of, as applicable, an undivided interest in the Leased Facilities (and associated Lease Power), the Leased Facilities themselves are part of the Generating Facilities and, as such, the Parties and, in some cases, AE Supply must coordinate the operation of the Leased Facilities and the Mon Power Facilities that, together, comprise the Generating Facilities. Such coordination shall be implemented primarily through the Operating Committee and shall be subject to the terms and conditions of this Lease. 4.2 Operating Committee. An operating committee (the “Operating Committee”) shall be established to carry out, coordinate, arrange for and administer the O&M Services pursuant to the provisions of this Lease and the Service Agreement. The Operating Committee shall consist of one representative each from PE and Mon Power. The representatives shall be indicated by the Parties to one another in writing no later than the Effective Date and each time thereafter that a Party wishes to make a change in representation. Each representative shall be authorized to commit the Party it represents to decisions made by the Operating Committee. All decisions of the Operating Committee must be unanimous. The duties of the Operating Committee shall include making determinations in respect of the operation and maintenance of the Leased Facilities (including re-rates, retirements and Capital Additions), the insurance requirements for any entity performing O&M Services, resolving disputes between the Parties that may arise under this Lease, acquiring necessary data, making calculations and determining values as required to implement the provisions of Article 6 (Compensation and Billing) and Article 12 (Events of Default; Remedies), coordinating as necessary with AE Supply, and any other issues described herein that contemplate action by the Operating Committee or are otherwise necessary to the proper administration of this Lease. The Operating Committee shall be expressly authorized to modify or supplement the terms and conditions of Article 8 (Insurance) by documenting such changes in a writing signed by both representatives of the Operating Committee (but without the necessity of a formal amendment signed by the Parties). 4.3 Allocation of Fixed and Variable Costs. Each Party shall have ultimate control over, and responsibility for its portion of the Generating Facilities during the Term, and shall bear its proportionate share of the fixed and variable costs and expenses (including all fuel costs and costs associated with the acquisition of necessary emission allowances) with respect to its portion of the Generating Facilities in accordance with the terms and conditions of Article 6 (Compensation and Billing). 4.4 Capital Addition. Neither Party shall, without the prior written consent of the Operating Committee, alter any of the Leased Facilities, or affix or install any accessories or devices on any of the Leased Facilities, if the same shall impair the originally intended function or use of such Leased Facilities or diminish their commercial value or useful life. Any and all unseverable fixtures to, additions to and/or improvements of any of the Leased Facilities, and any equipment or facilities installed on the Leased Facilities, and any additions and replacements made to any of the Leased Facilities (each such fixture, addition, improvement, installation or replacement, a “Capital Addition”), in all cases, shall constitute accessions to such Leased Facilities and ownership thereof shall immediately be vested in Mon Power. To the extent not otherwise agreed to by the Parties and subject to Section 6.2 (Environmental Control Cost Prepayment), Capital Additions made at the discretion of the Operating Committee shall be paid for by Mon Power, shall be for the benefit of Mon Power during the Term and shall be the property of Mon Power. Any Capital Additions or Environmental Control Equipment approved by the Operating Committee but financed by PE shall also become the property of Mon Power upon termination or expiration of this Lease, but shall be for the benefit of PE during the Term. PE shall utilize the Leased Facilities to provide Lease Power on a firm and continuous basis such that PE’s Service Obligations are supplied during the Term. ARTICLE 6 COMPENSATION AND BILLING 6.1 Monthly Usage Payment. As compensation for the grant to PE of its leasehold interest in and assignment of, as applicable, the Leased Facilities as set forth herein, in accordance with Section 6.3 (Invoicing) and Section 6.4 (Payments), PE agrees to pay Mon Power on a monthly basis in arrears a payment (the “Monthly Usage Payment”) to reflect PE’s actual use of the Leased Facilities, as measured by MWh sales associated with PE’s Service Obligations. From and after the Effective Date, in accordance with Section 6.3 (Invoicing) and Section 6.4 (payments), PE shall pay to Mon Power each month, in arrears, a Monthly Usage Payment calculated as follows: MUPi = [(AQi x UCi) - BOi] WHERE: MUPi = The Monthly Usage Payment (in $) for month i. AQi = The adjusted MWh quantity for month i, which is equal to the total MWh of wholesale power used to serve PE’s Service Obligations in month i under this Lease, up to the maximum amount of MWh available from the Leased Facilities in month i. UCi = The Usage Charge (in $/MWh) applicable to month i. The Usage Charge shall equal the Operating Costs for month i divided by the total MWh of wholesale power required to serve the combined Mon Power West Virginia (including West Virginia Power) and Potomac Edison West Virginia retail load for month i. BOi = The B&O Tax payment made by PE in month i in respect of the Capacity of the Leased Facilities. 6.2 Environmental Control Cost Prepayment. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the installation of Environmental Control Equipment and the performance of other Environmental Control Activities at the Fort Martin Generating Station, as contemplated by the Environmental Control Act, will be mutually beneficial to the Parties and is expected to result in an overall reduction in the cost of Lease Power. In consideration for such reduction in the cost of Lease Power and in order to finance in part the installation of Environmental Control Equipment and the performance of other Environmental Control Activities at the Fort Martin Generating Station, PE agrees that it shall prepay a portion of the Environmental Control Costs relating to the Fort Martin Generating Station, as follows: As contemplated in the applicable financing order issued pursuant to the Environmental Control Act, PE shall issue Environmental Control Bonds relating to the Fort Martin Generating Station and, as soon as practicable and in no event later than three (3) days after PE’s issuance of any such Environmental Control Bonds, PE shall pay to Mon Power all of the proceeds from such Environmental Control Bonds (any such payment, an “Environmental Control Cost Prepayment”). 6.3 Invoicing. Unless otherwise agreed to by the Parties, on or before the eighth (8th) Business Day of each month, Mon Power shall deliver to PE, via electronic transmission or other means agreed to by the Parties, an invoice (“Invoice”) that sets forth the total amount due for the previous calendar month under this Lease. The Invoice shall detail, among other things, (a) PE’s total Service Obligations (in MWh) for the applicable month, (b) the amount of MWh of Energy supplied pursuant to the terms and conditions of this Lease for the applicable month, (c) the Monthly Usage Payment to be paid pursuant to Section 6.1 (Monthly Usage Payment) and (d) any other adjustments set forth in this Lease. Unless the Operating Committee agrees otherwise, the Parties shall consolidate the invoicing of amounts due under this Lease with amounts due under the Service Agreement. 6.4 Payments. On the applicable Monthly Settlement Date, PE will pay to Mon Power the total amount due in the applicable Invoice. Payment of Invoices shall not relieve the paying Party from any other responsibilities or obligations it has under this Lease (other than the obligation to make such payment), including PE’s obligation to make any Environmental Control Payment under Section 6.2 (Environmental Control Cost Prepayment), nor shall such payment constitute a waiver of any claims arising hereunder. 6.5 Netting. Mon Power and PE shall discharge mutual debts and payment obligations due and owing to each other under this Lease and/or the Service Agreement, as of the applicable Monthly Settlement Date, such that all amounts owed by each Party to the other Party shall be reflected in a single amount due to be paid by the Party who owes it and received by the other Party, provided that the calculation of the net amount shall not include any disputed amounts being withheld pursuant to Section 6.6 (Billing Disputes and Adjustments of Invoices). 6.6 Billing Disputes and Adjustments of Invoices. (a) Within twelve (12) months of the date on which an Invoice is issued, Mon Power may, in good faith, adjust the Invoice to correct any errors. The adjustment shall include interest calculated at the Interest Rate from the original due date to the date of payment. Mon Power shall provide PE a written explanation of the basis for the adjustment. (b) Within twelve (12) months of the date on which an Invoice is issued or an Invoice is adjusted pursuant to Section 6.6(a) (Billing Disputes and Adjustments of Invoices), PE may, in good faith, dispute the correctness of such Invoice or adjustment, provided that PE has paid by the Monthly Settlement Date any portion of an Invoice that is not disputed. 6.7 Interest on Unpaid Balances. Interest on delinquent amounts, other than amounts in dispute as described in Section 6.6 (Billing Disputes and Adjustments of Invoices), shall be calculated at the Interest Rate from the original due date to the date of payment.
